CCN-DNS Project Development Log & Technology Stack
===================================================
Last updated: 2026-04-18

This log documents every tool, language, architecture decision, and bug fix
applied during the development of the DNS Resolution Service.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
1. Architecture
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Three-tier design:

  Tier 1 — Core (C++17)
    core/dns_resolver.cpp + dns_resolver.h
    Compiled to: core/dns_resolver.exe (Windows) / core/dns_resolver (Unix)
    Responsibilities:
      - Build and parse RFC 1035 DNS packets (binary wire format)
      - UDP transport with select() timeout (2 s/hop)
      - TCP fallback when TC (Truncation) bit is set (RFC 1035 §4.2.2)
      - Recursive walk: Root → TLD → Authoritative name servers
      - CNAME chain following (try same NS, then 3 random roots)
      - Glue-less NS resolution (isolated path vector per lookup)
      - Loop detection (visited-server set per resolution chain)
      - Thread-safe LRU + TTL cache (1 000 entries, std::list + std::map)
      - JSON serialisation to stdout (no external deps)

  Tier 2 — API (Python 3 / Flask)
    api/server.py
    Responsibilities:
      - Expose HTTP endpoints: /resolve /cache /metrics /benchmark /health
      - Spawn C++ subprocess; parse JSON from stdout
      - Python-side LRU+TTL cache (OrderedDict, sub-ms repeat hits)
      - Python fallback resolver — raw UDP to 8.8.8.8 with pointer
        decompression, used when C++ walk times out or returns failure
      - Rolling metrics history (1 000-query deque)
      - Benchmark: cold + warm local vs Google 8.8.8.8 vs Cloudflare 1.1.1.1
      - Subprocess timeout: 30 s (increased from 15 s for deep CNAME chains)
      - Flask threaded=True for concurrent request handling
      - CORS enabled for browser dashboard access

  Tier 3 — Web UI (HTML/CSS/JS)
    web/index.html, style.css, app.js
    Responsibilities:
      - DNS Lookup tab (input domain + record type, show answers)
      - Resolution Path visualiser (hop-by-hop server trace)
      - Cache viewer (live table with TTL countdown)
      - Metrics dashboard (latency stats, history table)
      - Benchmark tab (bar charts, winner highlight)
      - Packet Inspector (hex dump + RFC 1035 field annotation)

